Welcome to HTML
 also known as Hyper Text Markup Language
 it is the standard langauge used to design webpages by describing the structure of it
 it consists of a series of elements (labeled) that ultimately are displayed on the page 
 

<!DOCTYPE html>  --- This element is a declarant. It tells the browser that it is a HTML5 webpage

<html>  --- this is the root element
<head>  --- contains meta information about the page

<title>Page Title</title> --- specifies the title of a webpage
</head> --- closing indicator of head
<body>  --- container of visible contents 

<h1>This is a Heading</h1> ---- Largest header, ranging from h1 to h6
<p>This is a paragraph.</p> ---- Paragraph

</body> --- closing indicator body
</html> --- closing indicator of html

To create a file for html, can use Notepad, save as .htm or .html file--makes it easier to edit or access

Links
 <a href="https://www.w3schools.com">This is a link</a>

Images
 The source file (src), alternative text (alt), width, and height are provided as attributes:
 <img src="w3schools.jpg" alt="W3Schools.com" width="104" height="142">
 
Elements can be nested
Never skip the end tag!
Html is not case sensitive

<br> line break

All elements can have attributes that provide additional information about the element
They are specified by the start tage
name="value"
use lowercase attributes
Always quote attribute values
Double quotes around attribute values are the most common in HTML, but single quotes can also be used.

Href Attribute 
  specifies the url --- <a href="https://www.w3schools.com">Visit W3Schools</a>
  
src attribute
  specifies the path --- <img src="img_girl.jpg">
  only two ways to specify the URL :
    a Absolute URL - Links to an external image that is hosted on another website
    b Relative URL - Links to an image that is hosted within the website. Here, the URL does not include the domain name. 
      If the URL begins without a slash, it will be relative to the current page
      
Weight and Height attributes
  <img src="img_girl.jpg" width="500" height="600">
  
Alt attribute
   <img src="img_girl.jpg" alt="Girl with a jacket">
   <img src="img_typo.jpg" alt="Girl with a jacket">
   
Style attribute
  <tagname style="property:value;">
  The property is a CSS property. The value is a CSS value.
  <p style="color:red;">This is a red paragraph.</p>
  
Language Attribute
  <!DOCTYPE html>
  <html lang="en">
  
Title attribute
  <p title="I'm a tooltip">This is a paragraph.</p>
  
Bigger Heading
  <h1 style="font-size:60px;">Heading 1</h1>

Paragraphs

You cannot be sure how HTML will be displayed.
Large or small screens, and resized windows will create different results.
With HTML, you cannot change the display by adding extra spaces or extra lines in your HTML code.
The browser will automatically remove any extra spaces and lines when the page is displayed

<hr> Horizontal Rules
defines a thematic break in an HTML page, and is most often displayed as a horizontal rule

Line brakes <br> , it has no end tag
The HTML <pre> element defines preformatted text.

CSS Background Color 

  <body style="background-color:powderblue;">
  <h1>This is a heading</h1>
  <p>This is a paragraph.</p>
  </body>
or 
  <h1 style="background-color:powderblue;">This is a heading</h1>
  <p style="background-color:tomato;">This is a paragraph.</p>
  
Text Color
  CSS
  <h1 style="color:blue;">This is a heading</h1>
  <p style="color:red;">This is a paragraph.</p>
  
Text Font
  <h1 style="font-family:verdana;">This is a heading</h1>
  <p style="font-family:courier;">This is a paragraph.</p>
  
Text Size
  <h1 style="font-size:300%;">This is a heading</h1>
  <p style="font-size:160%;">This is a paragraph.</p> 
  
Text Alignment -- horizontal
  <h1 style="text-align:center;">Centered Heading</h1>
  <p style="text-align:center;">Centered paragraph.</p>
  
Formatting
  several elements included: 
  <b> - Bold text    ----   <b>This text is bold</b>
  <strong> - Important text  ---- <strong>This text is important!</strong>
  <i> - Italic text  ---- <i>This text is italic</i>
  <em> - Emphasized text --- <em>This text is emphasized</em>
  <mark> - Marked text  --- <p>Do not forget to buy <mark>milk</mark> today.</p>
  <small> - Smaller text  --- <small>This is some smaller text.</small>
  <del> - Deleted text  --- <p>My favorite color is <del>blue</del> red.</p> -- Browsers will usually strike a line through deleted text
  <ins> - Inserted text --- 
<p>My favorite color is <del>blue</del> <ins>red</ins>.</p>
  <sub> - Subscript text -- <p>This is <sub>subscripted</sub> text.</p>
  <sup> - Superscript text ---- <p>This is <sup>superscripted</sup> text.</p>
  
  
  Contiued,...
